<DOC><DOCNO> AP891201-0166 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-01-89 2006EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-BusinessHighlights     12-01 0839</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0882</SECOND><DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Wall Street leaders declared an end totheir lengthy battle to keep banks out of the stocks and bondsbusiness, proposing to junk the law that has governed the nation'sbasic banking structure since the Depression.   Directors of the Securities Industry Association, at the tradegroup's annual convention, on Friday endorsed a proposal for newlegislation to let subsidiaries of banks ``engage in a broad rangeof securities and securities-related activities.''   At the same time, the SIA said its plan would let brokers engagein consumer banking businesses and join banks in having access tothe Federal Reserve's banking system.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government's chief economic forecastinggauge signaled a slowdown in October, but other evidence suggestedthat lower interest rates will keep the economy from toppling intoa recession.   The 0.4 percent drop in the Commerce Department's Index ofLeading Economic Indicators reported Friday fits in with theconsensus among analysts that the final quarter of this year andthe first three months of 1990 will see weak growth at best.   However, some analysts said a number of factors mitigated theunfavorable report.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The manufacturing sector provided furtherevidence of a weakening economy as purchasing executives reportedthat business slowed again in November at the nation's industrialcompanies.   The National Association of Purchasing Management, which chartseconomic trends with a monthly survey of purchasing executives,said Friday the economy deteriorated for the seventh straight monthas production levels declined for the fifth straight month.   The organization's Purchasing Managers Index fell to 46.6percent from 47.6 in October.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The first gain in single-family home buildingin nine months helped boost construction spending in October, thegovernment said in a report suggesting lower interest rates arehelping end a construction slump.   The Commerce Department said Friday that spending rose 1 percentto a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $420.1 billion.   The increase followed no change in September and a 1.5 percentgain in August. Construction spending fell in July and June.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nation's thrift institutions continued toshrink dramatically in September in preparation for tough newfinancial standards taking effect the coming week, the governmentsaid.   Assets at the nation's 2,903 thrifts shrank by $15.2 billion,breaking the record set in August of $13.3 billion, the Office ofThrift Supervision said Friday.   Meanwhile, a net of $8.9 billion in deposits was withdrawn fromthrifts, the most since February, which marked the second-heaviestoutflow on record. September was the 16th consecutive month ofoutflows.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The merchant shipping industry said PresidentBush's decision to bar Panamanian-flag vessels from U.S. portscould make shipowners pawns in diplomatic disputes.   The move might interrupt free trade and prove costly anddisruptive to shipowners, industry insiders said Friday.   Bush's ban, announced Thursday, goes into effect Jan. 31 and isone of various U.S. economic sanctions already in place againstPanama's leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.</TEXT><DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   PacifiCorp offered to acquire PinnacleWest Capital Corp., three weeks after proposing a buyout of thecompany's Arizona Public Service Co., its only profitable division.   PacifiCorp, which has interests in electric utilities in sevenWestern states, made its offer Friday contingent on the sale ofMeraBank, Pinnacle West's troubled savings bank subsidiary.   PacifiCorp offered to exchange 0.18 of a share of its own stockfor each outstanding Pinnacle West share. Based on PacifiCorp'scurrent stock price the offer has an indicated value of nearly $8 ashare, or a total of about $693.7 million.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Private exporting companies have sold theSoviet Union an additional 800,000 metric tons of U.S. corn fordelivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement, theAgriculture Department said.   The department said Friday that 100,000 tons of soybean mealalso were sold to the Soviet Union for 1989-90 delivery.   Orders since Oct. 1, the beginning of the agreement's new year,now total about 10.3 million tons of corn, 160,700 tons ofsoybeans, 705,000 tons of soybean meal and 7,100 tons of barley.</TEXT><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   For sale: Used 12-wheel truck, with trailer. Armygreen. Maximum speed 25 mph. Weight 62,000 pounds. Previously usedonly for hauling nuclear missiles.   That was one of the offerings Friday at an unusual Red Tag Saleput on by the Soviet Ministry of Defense and several semi-publicorganizations to recoup some of the cold cash spent in the Cold War.   The sale items were military support equipment for themedium-range nuclear missiles destroyed under a 1987 U.S.-Sovietagreement.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associted Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The stock market surged Friday, as the Dow Jones average of 30industrials jumped 41.38 points to 2,747.65, the 10th highest closeever.   Bond prices rose moderately.   The dollar advanced against other major currencies.   Oil futures prices rose sharply; corn and soybean prices fell;wheat futures were mixed, gold rose while silver fell; cattlefutures advanced and pork futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>